Setup
Prerequisites

Python 3.9+
Anaconda (recommended)

Install dependencies
bashpip install numpy pandas scikit-learn tensorflow flask matplotlib

Running the Project
Step 1 — Preprocessing
Run project_preprocessing.ipynb top to bottom.
Output: X_train.npy, X_val.npy, X_test.npy, y_train.npy, y_val.npy, y_test.npy
Each session is preprocessed into shape (200, 4):
FeatureDescriptiontimestamp_normTime normalised to [0, 1]event_typemove=0, click=1, release=2x_normX coordinate ÷ screen widthy_normY coordinate ÷ screen height
Split: 70% train · 15% val · 15% test (stratified)

Step 2 — Training
Run project_training.ipynb top to bottom.
Output: bot_detector_model.keras, training_history.png
Model Architecture
Input (200, 4)
    ↓
GaussianNoise(0.01)         ← augmentation / anti-overfit
    ↓
BiLSTM(64, return_seq=True) ← captures forward + backward patterns
    ↓
BiLSTM(32, return_seq=False)
    ↓
Dense(32, ReLU) + L2
    ↓
Dropout(0.4)
    ↓
Dense(1, Sigmoid)           ← outputs P(bot)

Optimizer: Adam (lr=3e-4)
Loss: BinaryCrossentropy with label_smoothing=0.1
Batch size: 64
Class weights: computed via sklearn to handle 3:1 bot:human imbalance
Early stopping: patience=15, monitoring val_loss

Training Results
MetricValueTest AUC0.871Test Precision (bot)98.8%Test Accuracy72.5%Test Recall (bot)64.3%Train/Val loss gap−0.02 (no overfitting)
Best weights restored from epoch 5. Early stopping triggered at epoch 20.

Step 3 — Evaluation
Run project_evaluation.ipynb top to bottom.
Output: Confusion matrix, ROC curve, confidence distribution plots.

Step 4 — Live Demo
bashpython app.py
Open http://localhost:5000 in your browser.
How it works:

A circle is drawn on the canvas with a moving guide dot
User traces the circle with their mouse
200 mouse events are captured (timestamp, event type, x, y)
Events are preprocessed identically to training data
Model predicts P(bot) → displayed as Human % and Bot %


Note: The app works even without a trained model (demo mode with simulated predictions). Place bot_detector_model.keras in the same folder as app.py to use the real model.


How the Model Works
The model learns temporal patterns in mouse movement sequences. Humans exhibit natural micro-jitter, acceleration curves, and irregular timing. Bots produce mechanically regular intervals, perfectly straight paths, or unnaturally smooth curves.
The output is a single sigmoid value — P(bot). Human probability = 1 - P(bot).
P(bot) ≥ 0.5  →  BOT
P(bot) < 0.5  →  HUMAN

